Context¶

The number of restaurants in New York is increasing day by day. Lots of students and busy professionals rely on those restaurants due to their hectic lifestyles. Online food delivery service is a great option for them. It provides them with good food from their favorite restaurants. A food aggregator company FoodHub offers access to multiple restaurants through a single smartphone app.

The app allows the restaurants to receive a direct online order from a customer. The app assigns a delivery person from the company to pick up the order after it is confirmed by the restaurant. The delivery person then uses the map to reach the restaurant and waits for the food package. Once the food package is handed over to the delivery person, he/she confirms the pick-up in the app and travels to the customer's location to deliver the food. The delivery person confirms the drop-off in the app after delivering the food package to the customer. The customer can rate the order in the app. The food aggregator earns money by collecting a fixed margin of the delivery order from the restaurants.

Objective¶

The food aggregator company has stored the data of the different orders made by the registered customers in their online portal. They want to analyze the data to get a fair idea about the demand of different restaurants which will help them in enhancing their customer experience. Suppose you are hired as a Data Scientist in this company and the Data Science team has shared some of the key questions that need to be answered. Perform the data analysis to find answers to these questions that will help the company to improve the business.

Data Description¶

The data contains the different data related to a food order. The detailed data dictionary is given below.

Data Dictionary¶

  • order_id: Unique ID of the order
  • customer_id: ID of the customer who ordered the food
  • restaurant_name: Name of the restaurant
  • cuisine_type: Cuisine ordered by the customer
  • cost: Cost of the order
  • day_of_the_week: Indicates whether the order is placed on a weekday or weekend (The weekday is from Monday to Friday and the weekend is Saturday and Sunday)
  • rating: Rating given by the customer out of 5
  • food_preparation_time: Time (in minutes) taken by the restaurant to prepare the food. This is calculated by taking the difference between the timestamps of the restaurant's order confirmation and the delivery person's pick-up confirmation.
  • delivery_time: Time (in minutes) taken by the delivery person to deliver the food package. This is calculated by taking the difference between the timestamps of the delivery person's pick-up confirmation and drop-off information

# Purpose: Calculate various discrete statistical values for a specific column in a DataFrame
#
# Prerequisites:
#    Requires the developer to only send data that discrete statistics can safely be calculated for.
#    This function would require more extensive data validation checks and more robust exception handling.
#
# Inputs
#    data   : DataFrame object containing rows and columns of data
#    feature: str representing the column name to run statistics on
#
def calculate_statistics (data, feature):
        
    # Only calculate and print statistics if the feature is a single column string name and data is a DataFrame
    if isinstance(data,pd.DataFrame) and type(feature) == str:
        
        # For future, would like to use Describe to pull data types for each column
        # Then only perform the calculations and prints if of type Int64 or Float64
        
        # Calculate and print various discrete statistical values         
        print(f"Discrete Statistics for {feature}\n")
        print(f"Mean              : {data[feature].mean():.6f}")
        print(f"Mode              : {data[feature].mode()[0]}")
        print(f"Median            : {data[feature].median()}")
        print(f"Min               : {data[feature].min()}")
        print(f"Max               : {data[feature].max()}")   
        print(f"Standard Deviation: {data[feature].std():.6f}")
        print(f"Percentiles       : \n{data[feature].quantile([.25,.50,.75])}")

# Purpose: Create histogram plot to visualize the distribution of continuous numerical data
#      by dividing the data into bins and displaying the frequency of observations within each bin.
#      Histogram is useful for understanding the underlining distribution, shape, central tendency, 
#      and spread of the data.
#
# Inputs:
#
#      input_data: DataFrame object containing rows and columns of data
#      feature: str representing the column name to plot a histogram for
#      in_kde: boolean value; True: plot the kde density line; False: do not plot the kde line
#

def histogram(input_data, feature, in_kde=True):
    
    # Only proceed if the feature is a single column string name and data is a DataFrame
    if isinstance(input_data,pd.DataFrame) and type(feature) == str:
        
        #stores the x axis left and right buffer size
        buffer=5
            
        #set the x limits based on the minimum and maximum values for x-axis feature
        xmin_value = int(input_data[feature].min())
        xmax_value = int(input_data[feature].max())
        plt.xlim(xmin_value-buffer,xmax_value+buffer)
        
        #plot the histogram using the buffersize
        sns.histplot(data=input_data, x=feature, kde=in_kde);
        
        #set the title, x and y labels
        plt.title('Histogram of '+ feature)
        plt.xlabel(feature)
        plt.ylabel('Frequency')
        
        plt.show()

# Purpose: Create a Boxplot, for a particular column/feature, to visually summarize the distribution
#      of a continuous numerical variable and to identify potential outliers within the data.
#
# Inputs:
#
#      input_data: DataFrame object containing rows and columns of data
#      feature: str representing the column name to plot a count plot graph for
#      in_vert: False (display horizontal); True (display vertically)
#      in_showfliers: True (show the outliers); False (do not show outliers)
#      in_showlabels: True (show boxplot labels for Max,Q3,Median,Q1, and Min); False (do not show labels)
#

    #label translater key
    label_translator = {'caps 0': 'Min', 'caps 1': 'Max', 'whiskers 0': 'Q1', 'whiskers 1': 'Q3','medians 0':'Median', 'boxes 0':'Box'}

        for i in ax.keys():
            for index,line in enumerate(ax[i]):

                # labels for outliers

                    line_x,line_y=line.get_xydata()[0]
                    
                    #if needed and in vertical mode, show the key boxplot labels
                    #revisit later to get labels working in horizontal mode
                    if (in_showlabels == True and in_vert == True):
                        label_key = f"{i} {index}"
                        label = f"{label_translator[label_key]}:{line_y:.2f}"

        plt.show()

# Purpose: Create a countplot to visualize the distribution of categorical variables.
#
# Inputs:
#
#     input_data: DataFrame object containing rows and columns of data
#     feature: str representing the column name to plot a count plot graph for
#     hue_type: used to add additional categorical data to plot
#
# Notes:
#     data.loc[data[feature]>x,'Type'].value_counts()
#     data.loc[data[feature]>x].shape
#
def countplot(input_data, feature, hue_type=None):
    # Only proceed if the feature is a single column string name and data is a DataFrame
    if isinstance(input_data,pd.DataFrame) and type(feature) == str:
        if (hue_type is None):
            sns.countplot(data=input_data, x=feature)
        else:
            sns.countplot(data=input_data, x=feature,hue=hue_type)
        
        plt.show();

# Purpose: Create a countplot; used to visualize counts for categorical data
#
# Inputs:
#
#     input_data: DataFrame object containing rows and columns of data
#     feature: str representing the column name to plot a count plot graph for (category column)
#     show_perc: value from [0,1] indicating the top % values to show in the countplot
#     label_count: True (show count labels); False (show percentage labels)
#
def countplot (input_data, feature, show_perc=1.0, label_count=True):
    if isinstance(input_data,pd.DataFrame) and type(feature) == str:
                
        #Set the figure size. However, revist this later to see if there is a robust way to increase the 
        #figure size based on the number of x-axis labels.
        plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))   
        
        #Perform a total counts, which sorts the list in descending order. Then grab the list of columns
        order_cols = input_data[feature].value_counts().index
        
        #Use the percentage value to determine how many of the top columns to show
        num_to_show = int(len(order_cols)*show_perc)
        
        #Grab the top columns to show in the count plot
        cols_to_show = input_data[feature].value_counts().nlargest(num_to_show).index
                
        #plot the top columns
        cp=sns.countplot(data=input_data,x=feature,order=cols_to_show)
        
        #rotate x labels for better readability
        plt.xticks(rotation=90)
        
        #set the title
        plt_title = f"Countplot for the top {show_perc*100}% {feature} values"
        plt.title(plt_title)
        
        # Apply some simple label formatting; remove the underscores and replace with a blank space
        cp.set_xlabel(feature.replace('_', ' ').title(), fontsize=15)
        
        #show values for each bar/patch. The labels will either be numerical values or percentages.
        for p in cp.patches:
            
            total_values = len(input_data[feature])
            
            #show count labels
            if label_count == True:
                label = p.get_height() 
            else:
                # show percentage label
                label = "{:.1f}%".format(100 * p.get_height() / total_values)
            
            cp.annotate(
                label, 
                (p.get_x()+p.get_width()/2.,p.get_height()),
                ha='center',
                va='center',
                xytext=(0,5), # set the label offset above the bar
                textcoords='offset points'
            )

        plt.show()

# Purpose: Create a scatterplot; typically used to visualize the relationship between two continuous variables.
#     It represents individual data points as dots on a two-dimensional plane, with one variable plotted on 
#     the x-axis and the other variable plotted on the y-axis.
#
# Inputs:
#
#     input_data: DataFrame object containing rows and columns of data
#     x_feature: str representing the x axis to plot (numberical column)
#     y_feature: str representing the y axis to plot (numberical column)
#
def scatterplot (input_data, x_feature, y_feature):
    
    #do some basic validation on the input parameters and then create the scatterplot
    if isinstance(input_data,pd.DataFrame) and type(x_feature) == str and type(y_feature)==str:
        plt.figure(figsize=(10,5))
        sns.scatterplot(data=input_data,x=x_feature,y=y_feature)
        
        #set the title
        plt_title = f"Scatterplot: {x_feature} vs {y_feature}"
        plt.title(plt_title)

        plt.show()

# Purpose: Create a linear regression plot. The lmplot is used to visualize a scatterplot along with the
# linear regression line (best linear fit).
#
# Inputs:
#
#     input_data: DataFrame object containing rows and columns of data
#     x_feature: str representing the x axis to plot (numberical column)
#     y_feature: str representing the y axis to plot (numberical column)
#     input_height: height of the plot
#     input_aspect: represents the ratio of the height to the width of each facet. can be set to "auto"
#
# Helpful tip:
#      input_data[[col,col2]].corr() - Calculates the correlation between 2 columns
#
def lmplot (input_data, x_feature, y_feature, input_height=5, input_aspect=2):
        
    #do some basic validation on the input parameters and then create the linear regression plot
    if isinstance(input_data,pd.DataFrame) and type(x_feature) == str and type(y_feature)==str:
        
        #supress the tight_layout warning
        with warnings.catch_warnings():
            warnings.filterwarnings("ignore",category=UserWarning,module="seaborn")
        
            #plot the linear reqression plot
            sns.lmplot(data=input_data,x=x_feature,y=y_feature,height=input_height,aspect=input_aspect)

            #stores the x axis buffer
            buffer=5
            
            #set the x limits based on the minimum and maximum values for x-axis feature
            xmin_value = input_data[x_feature].min()
            xmax_value = input_data[x_feature].max()
            plt.xlim(xmin_value-buffer,xmax_value+buffer)
            
            #set the title
            plt_title = f"Linear Regression Plot: {x_feature} vs {y_feature}"
            plt.title(plt_title)

            plt.show()

# Purpose: Create a catplot; supports multivariate analysis of 2+ categorical features; creates a grid
#     of scatterplots
#
# Inputs:
#
#     in_data: DataFrame object containing rows and columns of data
#     x_feature: list representing the column names to plot a histogram plot graph for each categorical column
#     y_feature: list representing the column names to plot a histogram plot graph for each numerical column
#     in_hue: str representing the hue column to display
#     in_col: str representing the categorical column to create multiple plots for
#     in_kind: str representing the kind of plot.  Valid values are: box, swarm, strip, violin
#     in_pallete: str representing the pallete. Valid values are: deep, muted, bright, pastel, dark, colorblind
#     in_xorder:
#
def catplot (in_data,x_feature,y_feature,in_hue=None,in_col=None,in_kind='box',in_palette='bright',in_xorder=None):
    
    #do some basic validation on the input parameters and then create the scatterplot
    if isinstance(in_data,pd.DataFrame):
        
        #supress the tight_layout warning
        with warnings.catch_warnings():
            warnings.filterwarnings("ignore",category=UserWarning,module="seaborn")   
        
            # set the number of graphs per row
            col_wrap_value=3
                    
            # call countplot with various different optional values like: hue and col input parameters
            if (in_hue is None and in_col is None):
                sns.catplot(data=in_data,x=x_feature,y=y_feature,kind=in_kind, col_wrap=col_wrap_value,legend=True)
            elif (in_hue is None and in_col != None): # if col value is provided, use that in catplot call
                sns.cattplot(data=in_data,x=x_feature,y=y_feature,col=in_col,kind=in_kind,col_wrap=col_wrap_value,legend=True)
            elif (in_hue != None and in_col is None): # if hue value is provided, use that in catplot call
                sns.catplot(data=in_data,x=x_feature,y=y_feature,hue=in_hue,kind=in_kind,col_wrap=col_wrap_value,legend=True)
            else: # if both the hue and col values are provided, use them both in the catplot call
                sns.catplot(data=in_data,x=x_feature,y=y_feature,hue=in_hue, col=in_col,kind=in_kind,col_wrap=col_wrap_value,legend=True)
 
            #rotate x labels for better readability
            plt.xticks(rotation=90)
        
            #set the order of the x labels
            if (in_xorder is not None):
                plt.gca().set_xticklabels(in_xorder)

            plt.show()

            # Select only the numerical columns

            sns.pairplot(data=in_data[numeric_columns])
            plt.show()

#
# Inputs:

#     input_data: DataFrame object containing rows and columns of data

Observations:¶

  • The statistical summary of the order_id and customer_id columns will not yield meaningful insights as they are unique identifiers for the FoodHub orders and customers.
  • The average cost of an order is 16.50 US dollars. The range of the cost of orders is from $4.47 to $35.41 US dollars. For the most part this is usual, but there may be indications of outliers for both the minimum and maximum cost of the order. The small minimum order of \$4.63 could be attributed to drink orders or a small prepared item such as a bagel, pastry, etc.
  • 75% of the orders cost $22.30; which is not too far off from the mean. This may indicate that the restaurants in the area cater to the same type of clientele.
  • On average the food preparation time is 27.37 minutes. The range of the food preparation time is from 4.63 minutes to 35.00 minutes; which is usual.
  • On average the delivery time is 24.16 minutes. The range of the delivery time is 15.00 min to 33 min; which is usual.
  • In analyzing the minimum cost of an order of $4.47 US dollars and the minimum food preparation time of 20 min this seems a little unusal. A meal costing $4.47 indicates a very simple meal or drink, but the minimum food preparation time of 20 min may warrant further investigations. Delays in pick-up times may also be a factor in this descrepency.

Question 9: What percentage of the orders cost more than 20 dollars? [2 marks]¶

In [283]:
#initialize variables
count_greater_than_20=0
total_orders=0

#Iterate through each row/order
for index, row in df.iterrows():
    
    #increment the total order counter; used to calculate %
    total_orders += 1
    
    #grab the cost of the order
    cost_of_order = row['cost_of_the_order']
    
    #if the cost of the order is greater than 20 then count it
    if cost_of_order > 20:
        count_greater_than_20 += 1

print('Total orders costing more than $20:',count_greater_than_20)
print('Total number of orders:',total_orders)
print('% of orders more than $20: {}%'.format (round(count_greater_than_20/total_orders*100,2)))

Question 13: The company wants to provide a promotional offer in the advertisement of the restaurants. The condition to get the offer is that the restaurants must have a rating count of more than 50 and the average rating should be greater than 4. Find the restaurants fulfilling the criteria to get the promotional offer. [3 marks]¶

In [298]:
# Make a copy of the data because we're going to add an integer column for ratings that exist.
#
# Interpretation Assumption:
#    Assuming a rating count > 50 means that a restaurant must have more than 50 ratings from customers.
#       This does not mean the sum of the ratings for a restaurant must be more than 50. If this was the case
#       then the .count() would be changed to .sum()
#
# Cleanup Rule:
#    When value = 'Not given' insert a None value
#    Rationale: placing a None value will not positively nor negatively impact the rating total calculation
#

#make a copy of the dataframe
df_copy = df.copy()

#Create a new rating integer column and transform any Not given ratings to None.
#Decision made to leave original column just in case the original ratings column is needed again.
df_copy["rating_int"] = df["rating"].apply(
    lambda x: int(x) if x != "Not given" else None
)

# Total the ratings for each restaurant
df_rating_total = df_copy.groupby(['restaurant_name'])["rating_int"].count().to_frame().reset_index()
df_rating_total.columns = ['Restaurant Name', 'Rating Count']
df_rating_total.sort_values(by='Rating Count',ascending=False, inplace=True)

# Calculate the average rating for each restaurant
df_avg_rating = df_copy.groupby(['restaurant_name'])["rating_int"].mean().to_frame().reset_index()
df_avg_rating.columns = ['Restaurant Name', 'Average Rating']
df_avg_rating.sort_values(by='Average Rating',ascending=False, inplace=True)

# Now merge the two lists together using the restaurant name as key
merged_df = pd.merge(df_rating_total,df_avg_rating,on="Restaurant Name", how='inner')

# Filter the merged list only showing restaurants that have a rating count greater than 50
winners_df = merged_df[(merged_df['Rating Count']>50) & (merged_df['Average Rating']>4)]
winners_df

Question 14: The company charges the restaurant 25% on the orders having cost greater than 20 dollars and 15% on the orders having cost greater than 5 dollars. Find the net revenue generated by the company across all orders. [3 marks]¶

In [299]:
# Calculate the net revenue per order using the rules in Question 14
df_copy = df.copy()

#create a new column to store the net revenue per order based on the charge rates.
#if cost of order is greater than $20, then apply a 25% charge;
#else if cost of order is greater than $5 but less then $20, then apply a 15% charge;
# else if cost is less than $5, then no cost (may want to consider charging a flat fee)
df_copy['net_order_revenue'] = df_copy['cost_of_the_order'].apply(
    lambda cost: cost - cost*.25 if cost > 20 else cost-cost*.15 if cost > 5 else cost
)

total_net_revenues = df_copy['net_order_revenue'].sum()
print(f"Total Net Revenues: ${total_net_revenues:,.2f}")

# now sum the total net revenues made for each restaurant.
df_net_revenues = df_copy.groupby(['restaurant_name'])['net_order_revenue'].sum().to_frame().reset_index()
df_net_revenues.columns = ['Restaurant Name', 'Net Revenue']
df_net_revenues.sort_values(by='Net Revenue',ascending=False, inplace=True)

num_top_restaurants=12
print(f"\nTop {num_top_restaurants} restaurants generate {df_net_revenues.head(num_top_restaurants)['Net Revenue'].sum()/total_net_revenues*100:.2f}% of the total revenues.")
print(f"\nThe top {num_top_restaurants} Net Revenue generating restaurants")
df_net_revenues.head(num_top_restaurants)

Conclusion and Recommendations¶

Question 17: What are your conclusions from the analysis? What recommendations would you like to share to help improve the business? (You can use cuisine type and feedback ratings to drive your business recommendations.) [6 marks]¶

Conclusions:¶

The dataset from the FoodHub was analyzed to get a better understanding about the demand of the different restaurants and customer experiences. These insights can then be utilized to provide recommendations that will help enhance their customer experience; thus ultimately driving increased company revenues. With the help of descriptive analysis and visualizations, the following insights have been drawn:

  • The top four (4) cuisine types that are generating 82.6% of the orders are as follows:
    1. American
    2. Japanese
    3. Italian
    4. Chinese

  • Weekend orders contribute 71.2%; while weekday orders contribute: 28.8%
    • Customers ordering American food will pay more on the weekends than on the weekdays.
    • Customers ordering Chinese food will pay more on the weekdays than on the weekends.

  • Delivery times on the weekends is approximately six (6) minutes less than on the weekdays.

  • The top five (5) restaurants in terms of order counts are as follows:
    1. Shake Shake
    2. The Meatball Shop
    3. Blue Ribbon Sushi
    4. Blue Ribbon Fried Chicken
    5. Parm

  • There are no ratings below a 3; and approximately 39% of the ratings are "Not given"
    • In the Middle Eastern cuisine, it appears that customers are paying top dollar, more than \$30, on the weekday resulting in a mediocore rating of 3.
    • In the Thai cuisine, if a rating was given it was either a 4 or 5. Therefore, it is likely the Thai restaurants are well received and liked by customers.

Recommendations:¶

  • Cuisine Specific Promotion Strategies
    • American, Japanese, Italian, and Chinese Cuisines
      • Introduce weekend promotions or exclusive menu items to capitalize on higher weekend orders.
      • Implement targeted customer marketing campaigns to promote these cuisines or offer discounts.
      • Implement exclusive marketing campaigns for the top 12 earning restaurants to help promote their specialty or seasonal items.
      • To help improve weekday orders, run promotionals (reduced delivery fees, increase customer loyalty points, etc.) for Chinese restaurants since customers ordering Chinese food tend to pay more on the weekdays.
      • To help improve weekend orders, run promotionals for American restaurants since customers ordering American food tend to pay more on the weekends.
      • Explore opportunities for upselling or cross selling to increase the average order size; thus increasing the net revenue per order.
    • Middle Eastern Cuisine
      • Leverage high weekday average cost of orders:
        • Analyze customer feedback to identify areas for improvement and if necessary provide this information to the impacted Middle Eastern restaurants.
        • Recommend adjusting pricing or offering weekday specials to help improve ratings.
        • For the customers who provided three star ratings in this area, provide targeted customer discount incentives to improve chances of repeat business.
    • Thai Cuisine:
      • Leverage the positive customer sentiment for Thai cuisine:
        • Send targeted customer marketing promotions, to those ordering in the top four cuisines that are not ordering Thai.
        • Work with local Thai restaurants to expand or enhance the Thai menu to help expand its customer base.
  • Customer Loyalty Program
    • Develop a customer loyalty program that provides incentives to repeat customers. Incentivies may include discounts, exclusive deals, loyalty points, etc.
    • Offer customer loyalty points for every review provided. Customer loyalty points can be redeemed for discounts.
    • Using order history, create personalized promotions based on customer ordering preferences.
  • Delivery Driver Loyalty Program
    • Create a delivery driver loyalty program to build a strong base of long-term delivery drivers.
    • Add delivery driver incentives for weekday deliveries to help reduce the overall weekday delivery times.
  • Rating Improvement Strategies
    • Provide customers with incentives (loyalty points, discounts, etc.) to provide ratings and reviews.
    • Provide restaurants with customer review feedback summaries to help restaurants improve overall ratings.
    • Verify with Foodhub development team that the application is allowing and/or capturing rating values of one (1) and two (2).
  • Improved Data Analytics
    • Recommend procuring funds to gather day and time information for all time fields; enabling detailed analytics on day of week and time of day.
    • Recommend procuring funds to gather detailed driver delivery information (e.g., number of pickups, $ of on-time deliveries, and delivery driver ratings). Delivery driver data could be used to help improve loyalty among drivers; which will result in improved pick-up times and customer satisfaction.
